      "source": [
        "# **Introduction**"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "vGzZjsQtD9-C"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "Credit risk management remains a cornerstone of financial institution stability, with credit card default prediction representing one of the most challenging and impactful applications of machine learning in finance. Traditional supervised approaches rely heavily on historical labeled data, which is often incomplete, delayed, or biased toward previously observed failure patterns. In contrast, unsupervised anomaly detection offers a complementary paradigm: identifying clients whose financial behavior deviates significantly from the norm, potentially signaling emerging risk before explicit default occurs.\n",
        "\n",
        "This report presents an application of the Isolation Forest algorithm to the UCI Credit Card Default dataset comprising 30,000 client records from Taiwan. By leveraging repayment histories, billing patterns, and credit utilization metrics, we demonstrate how unsupervised learning can isolate financially anomalous profiles and evaluate their alignment with actual default outcomes. The analysis addresses both technical performance and practical considerations for deploying anomaly detection in regulated financial environments, where interpretability, fairness, and operational feasibility are paramount"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "gshqu5vVEC59"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "# **Objective**"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "KgLez27_EC-b"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "The primary objectives of this study are:\n",
        "1. Preprocess and engineer meaningful financial features from raw credit card data, focusing on variables that capture repayment behavior, credit exposure, and cash flow dynamics.\n",
        "2. Train and validate an Isolation Forest model with justified hyperparameters, establishing a baseline for unsupervised anomaly detection in credit portfolios.\n",
        "3. Quantify and characterize detected anomalies by comparing statistical properties (medians, ranges) and default rates between outlier and inlier groups.\n",
        "4. Assess model sensitivity to the contamination parameter, evaluating how threshold selection impacts outlier volume, risk precision, and operational utility.\n",
        "5. Provide actionable recommendations on the applicability, limitations, and ethical considerations of deploying Isolation Forest in real-world financial or educational risk-monitoring systems."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "IubAEBYSEDBr"
      }
    },
